    {
      "created_time": "2017-11-26T18:08:58+0000",
      "message": "Since I am not knowledgeable about the subject I asked David who is very knowledgeable and this is his opinion:\nNet neutrality is a complicated issue with no easy or definitive conclusion on a single side. Take for example the case of Netflix and Comcast prior to net neutrality. Comcast claimed Netflix was sending more data than it was receiving thus creating an imbalance in peering relationship with the provider for Netflix. Comcast demanded more money from Netflix in return they would provide higher level of access on their network. This is good for customers with lower bandwidth, they are still able to subscribe to Netflix and get reasonable downloads, more business for Netflix, more income for Comcast. This is also bad because you are essentially putting a toll on the internet, pay us this fee or we don‚Äôt carry your traffic. This could cause rates to go up for Netflix. On one hand you have the ability to pay for better service on the other you may be charged for access you take for granted. I would err on the side of keeping net neutrality but am interested to see how the industry will react to the change.",
      "id": "10157614223046509_10157619025846509"
    }
